The Federal Executive Council (FEC) on Wednesday approved a proposed budget of N13.08trn Capital Expenditure for the 2021 budget proposal has been set at N2.083trn. The Minister for Finance, Budget and National Planning, Zainab Ahmed, who addressed the media after the weekly FEC meeting at the state laid some key highlights of the proposed budget. READ ALSO: The minister put the oil benchmark has been pegged at $40 per barrel with a production level of 1.86 million barrels per day and an exchange of N379 per dollar. The proposal targets a Gross Domestic Product (GDP) growth of three per cent and an inflation rate of 11.95 per cent. The Minister, had the Minister of State for Budget and National Planning, Clement Agba; the Minister for Information and Culture Alhaji Lai Mohammed and the Director-General of the Budget Office, Mr Ben Akabueze by her side during the address to the media. To kick of ceremonies marking Nigeria”s 60-year anniversary, President Muhammadu Buhari will for the first time in his presidency make the October 1 address from Eagle Square. Special Adviser to the President on Media, Femi Adesina, said in a statement on Wednesday that the event would be covered live on state television and radio. He said, “As part of activities commemorating the 60th Independence anniversary of the country, President Muhammadu Buhari will address the nation from the Eagle Square, Abuja, on Thursday, October 1, 2020.” Adesina said, “The live address will commence after the Anniversary Parade beginning at 10am which will be covered by major television and radio stations especially the network services of the Nigerian Television Authority (NTA) and the Federal Radio Corporation of Nigeria (FRCN). “Please note that in view of the open-air live address, the traditional early morning October 1 Presidential Broadcast will not feature on Thursday.”